            <cb/>
            <lb break="yes"/>
            <p>Mr. <hi rendition="#k">Murchison</hi>, the general secretary, in referring to<lb break="yes"/>the number of foreigners present, announced the presence<lb break="yes"/>of a deputation from the Italian Association for the Advance-<lb break="no"/>ment of Science, which will be held at Pisa, in October;<lb break="yes"/>of a deputation to represent a special meeting of the<lb break="yes"/>Geological Society of France, which will be held at Bo-<lb break="no"/>logne, in October; and from the Association of German<lb break="yes" />Naturalists, which will be held at Clermont, next month.<lb break="yes"/>He also read a letter from Baron Humboldt, addressed to<lb break="yes"/>J. L. Moillet, Esq., of which the following is a transla-<lb break="no"/>tion:&#x2014;</p>
            <lb break="yes"/>
            <div n="2">
                <dateline>
                    <hi rendition="#et">&#x201C;Potsdam, 26th June, 1839.</hi>
                </dateline>
                <lb break="yes"/>
                <p>&#x201C;I cannot express to you, sir, how much I have been<lb break="yes" />flattered by the expression of the kind and friendly feelings<lb break="yes" />contained in your letter of the 24th of May last. The in-<lb break="no" />vitation of the distinguished British Association for the<lb break="yes" />Advancement of Science has penetrated me with the most<lb break="yes"/>lively sense of gratitude; I entreat you, sir, to accept the<lb break="yes"/>assurance of it, and to be the interpreter of my respectful<lb break="yes"/>sentiments to the committee. I regret extremely not to<lb break="yes"/>be able to avail myself of your liberal offer. My residence<lb break="yes"/>in your house, its proximity to a town whose wealth is the<lb break="yes"/>fruit of intelligence, and the hope of meeting there some of<lb break="yes"/>my friends, would have greatly enhanced the gratification<lb break="yes"/>which must arise from the imposing re-union of the<lb break="yes"/>scientific men of England. It certainly is not the sacrifice<lb break="yes"/>of time, nor the dread of locomotion, which detains me<lb break="yes"/>on the continent. My position no longer affords me the<lb break="yes"/>freedom which I enjoyed in the forests of the Orinoco, or<lb break="yes"/>in the wilds of the Oby. The King, whom I am in the<lb break="yes"/>habit of accompanying in his travels, does not set out this<lb break="yes"/>year before the middle of July, and his absence in Bohemia<lb break="yes"/>and in the mountains of Silesia, will be protracted until<lb break="yes"/>the early part of September. Accept, sir, the expression<lb break="yes"/>of my high consideration, and of the affectionate regard<lb break="yes"/>with which I have the honour to be,</p>
                <lb break="yes"/>
                <closer>
                    <salute>
                        <hi rendition="#et">&#x201C;Your most obedient and humble servant,<lb break="yes"/>(Signed) &#x201C;<hi rendition="#k">The Baron de Humboldt.</hi>
                        </hi>
                    </salute>&#x201C;J. L. Moillet, Esq.&#x201D;<lb break="yes"/>
                </closer>
            </div>
            <lb break="yes"/>
